articles.author: BASSEM MROUE and WAFAA SHURAFA
articles.description: BEIRUT (AP) — Israeli strikes killed 38 people in Gaza and three journalists in Lebanon on Friday as growing worries about supply shortages in Gaza and international pressure for a cease-fire mounted.
articles.title: Israeli strikes kill 38 people in Gaza's Khan Younis and 3 journalists in southern Lebanon

articles.author: COLLEEN LONG, DARLENE SUPERVILLE and NADIA LATHAN
articles.description: HOUSTON (AP) — Vice President Kamala Harris will team up with Beyoncé on Friday for a rally in solidly Republican Texas aimed at highlighting the perilous medical fallout from the state's strict abortion ban and putting the blame squarely on Donald Trump.
articles.title: Harris, Beyoncé team up for a Texas rally on abortion rights and hope battleground states hear them

articles.author: DAN MERICA
articles.description: WASHINGTON (AP) — Donald Trump said Thursday that China's leader would handle Vice President Kamala Harris “like a baby” if she's elected to the White House, as the former president and his top allies increasingly have moved to infantilize the Democratic nominee.
articles.title: Trump says China's leader will bully Harris 'like a baby' as his allies try to infantilize her

articles.author: CLAIRE GALOFARO and KIM TONG-HYUNG
articles.description: HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) — The 50-year-old newspaper was turning yellow and its edges fraying, so she had it laminated, not as a memento but as proof — America made a promise to her, and did not keep it.
articles.title: ‘US doesn’t see me as an American’: Thousands of adoptees live in limbo without citizenship

articles.author: JOSHUA GOODMAN and MOLLY QUELL
articles.description: THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) — As the International Criminal Court’s top prosecutor sought war crimes charges this year against Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over actions in Gaza, he was engulfed in a very different personal crisis playing out behind the scenes.
articles.title: International court prosecutor who charged Netanyahu faces sexual misconduct accusation

articles.author: STEVE PEOPLES
articles.description: NEW YORK (AP) — Progressive Democrats warn Kamala Harris risks losing the support of a small but significant portion of her political base unless she changes her campaign's closing message — and its messengers — immediately.
articles.title: Progressives warn Harris must change her closing message as the election looms

articles.author: STEFANIE DAZIO, JAIMIE DING and CHRISTOPHER WEBER
articles.description: LOS ANGELES (AP) — Erik and Lyle Menendez still have a long way to go before they can walk out of prison, even though the Los Angeles County district attorney has recommended their life-without-parole sentences be thrown out and the brothers be resentenced and immediately eligible for parole.
articles.title: Erik and Lyle Menendez are a step closer to leaving prison, but freedom won't come quickly

articles.author: MARCIA DUNN
articles.description: CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) — Four astronauts returned to Earth on Friday after a nearly eight-month space station stay extended by Boeing's capsule trouble and Hurricane Milton.
articles.title: 4 astronauts return to Earth after being delayed by Boeing's capsule trouble and Hurricane Milton

articles.author: TERRY SPENCER
articles.description: MIAMI (AP) — The last Kmart on the U.S. mainland sits at the west end of a busy suburban Miami shopping center, quiet and largely ignored.All around it are thriving chain stores attracting steady streams of customers in sectors where the former box-store chain was once a major player: Marshalls, Hobby Lobby, PetSmart and Dollar Tree.
articles.title: In a suburban Miami shopping center, Kmart's last 'Blue Light Specials' flicker

articles.author: R.J. RICO
articles.description: If Donald Trump wins the presidential election, Republicans hope he will fulfill a longstanding GOP goal of privatizing the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, which have been under government control since the Great Recession.
articles.title: Allies hope a Trump win changes the system for mortgages. Some warn it will make them pricier
